Duality between quark-quark and quark-antiquark pairing 
 in 1+1 dimensional large  models   
Michael Thies(Electronic address: thies@theorie3.physik.uni-erlangen.de)   
Institut fur Theoretische Physik III
 
Universitat Erlangen-Nurnberg
 
Staudtstrasse 7
 
D-91058 Erlangen
 
Germany  
  
 
We identify a canonical transformation which maps the chiral Gross-Neveu model onto a recently
proposed Cooper pair model. Baryon number and axial charge are interchanged. The same physics
can be described either as chiral symmetry breaking (quark-antiquark pairing) or as superconductivity
(quark-quark pairing).
 

11.10.Kk 






A few years ago, Chodos, Minakata and Cooper proposed a 1+1 dimensional field theoretical
model which can be solved in the -expansion and illustrates nicely the phenomenon of Cooper pairing.
Independently, the same model has been analyzed by Kleinert and Babaev at finite  in
 dimensions, in a somewhat different context.
It is closely related to the Gross-Neveu model from which it differs through
the particular form of the four-fermion coupling,
 
Due to the arrangement of flavour indices, the vacuum develops a 
condensate and breaks spontaneously the  symmetry (baryon number),
at least in the large  limit. 
Other properties
at zero temperature and chemical potential derived in Ref. are strongly reminiscent of the
Gross-Neveu model, 
namely asymptotic freedom, dynamical fermion mass generation and a massless "would be" Goldstone boson
(here: a "diquark").
Later on, this model has been augmented by a scalar-scalar interaction of  
Gross-Neveu type. The competition between 
and  condensates was studied in detail at finite temperature and
chemical potential. Given the current interest in color superconductivity in
the context of Quantum Chromodynamics (for a recent review, see e.g.), such a
pedagogical model is highly welcome.

In this short note, we would like to clarify the relation between the Cooper pair model(hereafter referred to as "BCS model") and the standard Gross-Neveu model with continuous chiral symmetry
("NJL model"). Confirming the results of Ref., we will show that at zero
chemical potential the two theories are equivalent; they can in fact be mapped into each other
by a canonical transformation. At non-zero chemical potential the two
theories are no longer equivalent but nevertheless closely related. This also sheds
some new light onto a recent work by Ohwa. This author finds a chiral crystal structure of baryonic matter
in the NJL model, confirming Ref., whereas he sees no violation of translational invariance
in the BCS model. 

